msgid "Component accessor, not a witness constructor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:0
msgid "`index_2d_col()`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:126
msgid ""
"`index_2d_row()` and `index_2d_col()` return plain `usize` -- they give you "
"the components for arithmetic, but cannot be used to index into a "
"`DisjointSlice`. Only the linearized result earns a `ThreadIndex`. Likewise, "
"2D uniqueness assumes the launch has no active Z dimension. A `domain = 2` "
"prepared launch proves that; a raw launch must assert it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:132
msgid "How `index_2d` is type-safe"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:134
msgid ""
"`index_2d::<S>()` is const-generic over the row stride. The witness comes "
"back as `ThreadIndex<'kernel, Index2D<S>>`, and a `DisjointSlice<T, "
"Index2D<S>>` only accepts that exact `S`. Two threads cannot mint witnesses "
"with different strides and feed them into the same slice -- the type system "
"rejects it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:140
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn ok(mut out: DisjointSlice<u32, Index2D<128>>) {\n"
"    if let Some(idx) = thread::index_2d::<128>() {  // matches\n"
"        if let Some(slot) = out.get_mut(idx) { *slot = 1; }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn rejected(mut out: DisjointSlice<u32, Index2D<128>>) {\n"
"    if let Some(idx) = thread::index_2d::<256>() { // ⛔ Index2D<256> != "
"Index2D<128>\n"
"        if let Some(slot) = out.get_mut(idx) { *slot = 1; }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:156
msgid ""
"The witness is also `!Send + !Sync + !Copy + !Clone`, and its `'kernel` "
"lifetime is borrowed from a stack-local scope the macros inject -- so a "
"thread can't park its `ThreadIndex` in shared memory and have a neighbour "
"pick it up later, and the witness can't outlive the kernel body."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:161
msgid "Truly runtime strides: `unsafe index_2d_runtime`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:163
msgid ""
"Some kernels really do receive their stride at launch time (e.g. matrix "
"dimensions known only on the host). For those cases there's a corresponding "
"witness `Runtime2DIndex` and an `unsafe` constructor:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:167
msgid "let idx = unsafe { thread::index_2d_runtime(n)? };\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:171
msgid ""
"The `unsafe` is the contract: every thread in the kernel that feeds a "
"`Runtime2DIndex` into the same `DisjointSlice<T, Runtime2DIndex>` must have "
"used the same `n`. The type system *can't* prove this -- two "
"`ThreadIndex<'_, Runtime2DIndex>` values produced under different runtime "
"strides have the same type. If you can pin the stride at compile time, "
"prefer `index_2d::<S>()`. If you can't, the `unsafe` keyword on "
"`index_2d_runtime` is the marker that the safety obligation is yours."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:179
msgid "The GEMM pattern"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:181
msgid ""
"For const-stride 2D kernels (the common case -- tiled GEMM, stencil kernels, "
"image kernels with a fixed channel count), the const-generic form is the "
"safe default:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:185
msgid ""
"const STRIDE: usize = 1024;     // C is M x STRIDE\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn gemm(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32, "
"Index2D<STRIDE>>, m: u32) {\n"
"    let row = thread::index_2d_row();\n"
"    if let Some((c_elem, _)) = c.get_mut_indexed() {\n"
"        // col < STRIDE is guaranteed by `Some` -- no manual check needed\n"
"        if row < m as usize {\n"
"            // ... compute dot product into a local accumulator `sum` ...\n"
"            *c_elem = alpha * sum + beta * (*c_elem);\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:201
msgid ""
"For runtime strides, the same shape works but the linearisation step is "
"explicit and `unsafe`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:204
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn gemm_runtime(a: &[f32], b: &[f32], mut c: DisjointSlice<f32, "
"Runtime2DIndex>, m: u32, n: u32) {\n"
"    let n = n as usize;             // ONE binding, ONE stride value\n"
"    let row = thread::index_2d_row();\n"
"\n"
"    // SAFETY: every thread in the kernel sees the same `n` (kernel arg).\n"
"    if let Some(c_idx) = unsafe { thread::index_2d_runtime(n) } {\n"
"        if row < m as usize {\n"
"            // ... compute dot product ...\n"
"            if let Some(c_elem) = c.get_mut(c_idx) {\n"
"                *c_elem = alpha * sum + beta * (*c_elem);\n"
"            }\n"
"        }\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:222
msgid ""
"The `if let Some` from `index_2d_runtime` replaces the manual `col < n` "
"guard you'd write in CUDA C++. The `row < m` check remains because it guards "
"against reading garbage from the input matrices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:226
msgid "What makes a kernel Tier 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:228
msgid "A kernel and its launch are fully safe -- Tier 1 -- when:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:230
msgid ""
"All mutable output access goes through `DisjointSlice::get_mut(ThreadIndex)`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:231
msgid "All inputs are shared immutable references (`&[T]`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:232
msgid "No shared memory, no raw pointers, no intrinsics beyond thread indexing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:233
msgid "The host uses a matching checked `PreparedLaunch<K>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:235
msgid ""
"Examples in this tier include `vecadd`, `helper_fn`, `generic`, "
"`host_closure`, and the naive GEMM kernels in the `gemm` and `async_mlp` "
"examples when launched through matching contracts. Their raw `LaunchConfig` "
"paths remain unsafe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:241
msgid "Tier 2: scoped `unsafe`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:243
msgid ""
"Not every kernel fits the \"one thread, one output element\" pattern. When "
"threads need to cooperate -- sharing data through fast on-chip memory, "
"communicating across lanes in a warp, or performing atomic updates -- you "
"need `unsafe`. The key property of Tier 2 is that the `unsafe` is *scoped* "
"and *auditable*: each block has a documented safety contract, and the rest "
"of the kernel remains safe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:250
#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "Shared memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:252
msgid ""
"Shared memory is fast, on-chip, and visible to every thread in a block. That "
"last property is exactly why it requires `unsafe` -- the borrow checker "
"cannot reason about 256 threads writing to the same `static mut` array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:256
msgid ""
"static mut TILE: SharedArray<f32, 256> = SharedArray::UNINIT;\n"
"\n"
"unsafe { TILE[ty * TILE_SIZE + tx] = value; }\n"
"\n"
"thread::sync_threads();\n"
"\n"
"let neighbor = unsafe { TILE[other_idx] };\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:266
msgid ""
"The contract: ensure no conflicting writes from concurrent threads without "
"synchronization. The `sync_threads()` barrier is the tool that makes this "
"work -- it guarantees all threads have finished writing before any thread "
"reads."
msgstr ""

