msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:301
msgid "Barriers and lifecycle"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:303
msgid ""
"The `ManagedBarrier` typestate API encodes the barrier lifecycle (`Uninit` -"
"> `Ready` -> `Invalidated`) in the type system, so you cannot wait on a "
"barrier that was never initialized or use one that has been invalidated. The "
"`init()` and `inval()` transitions still require `unsafe` because they "
"interact with the hardware, but the type states prevent the most common "
"mistakes at compile time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:296
msgid "`mbarrier_init`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:296
msgid "Must be called by exactly one thread; barrier must be in shared memory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:296
msgid "`mbarrier_arrive` / `mbarrier_wait`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:296
msgid "Barrier must be initialized; token must match"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:296
msgid "`ManagedBarrier` (typestate)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:296
msgid ""
"`init()` and `inval()` require `unsafe`; state machine enforced at compile "
"time"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:316
#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "Atomics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:318
msgid ""
"Atomic operations are safe to *call* once you have a valid atomic reference. "
"The `unsafe` surface is at construction -- creating a `DeviceAtomicU32` from "
"a raw pointer requires the caller to guarantee that the pointer is valid and "
"properly aligned:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:323
msgid ""
"let atom = unsafe { DeviceAtomicU32::new(ptr) };\n"
"atom.fetch_add(1, Ordering::Relaxed);  // safe call\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:328
msgid "Unchecked slice access"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:330
msgid ""
"When the \"one thread, one element\" model does not fit -- for instance, in "
"a warp-level reduction where only lane 0 writes the result -- "
"`DisjointSlice::get_unchecked_mut(usize)` provides an escape hatch:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:334
msgid ""
"if warp::lane_id() == 0 {\n"
"    let warp_idx = gid.get() / 32;\n"
"    // SAFETY: Only lane 0 of each warp writes; warp indices are unique\n"
"    unsafe { *out.get_unchecked_mut(warp_idx) = sum; }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:342
msgid ""
"The safety obligation is the same as the `ThreadIndex` system enforces "
"automatically: index in bounds, no two threads share the same index. The "
"difference is that you prove it yourself instead of letting the type system "
"do it for you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:349
msgid "Tier 3: raw hardware"
msgstr ""

