#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:381
msgid "What the borrow checker gives you"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:383
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide is not a DSL or a macro system -- it runs the real `rustc` "
"frontend on your kernel code. That means every safety guarantee Rust "
"provides on the CPU is also enforced on the GPU:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "Guarantee"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "How It Works"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Ownership and borrowing**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"Lifetime errors, use-after-free, and aliasing violations caught at compile "
"time"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Safe parallel writes**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"`DisjointSlice<T>` + `ThreadIndex` + matching prepared geometry prove that "
"writes do not race"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Explicit `unsafe` scoping**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"Raw pointer access requires `unsafe`, making obligations visible and "
"auditable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Convergent attribute enforcement**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"Sync primitives (barriers, fences, shuffles) marked `convergent` in the IR, "
"preventing the optimizer from moving or duplicating them across control flow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:394
msgid ""
"The first three are standard Rust. The fourth is GPU-specific: CUDA's `bar."
"sync`, fence, and warp shuffle instructions must not be duplicated or "
"reordered by the compiler. cuda-oxide marks them `convergent` in the IR so "
"that LLVM's optimization passes leave them alone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:401
msgid "The hard problems"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:403
msgid ""
"Rust's borrow checker was designed for single-threaded ownership with `Send`/"
"`Sync` for CPU concurrency. SIMT execution introduces patterns that the "
"borrow checker was never taught to reason about. Here is an honest "
"accounting of what cuda-oxide does *not* enforce today -- and why these "
"problems are solvable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:409
msgid "Thread-divergent control flow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:411
msgid ""
"Rustc's JumpThreading MIR optimization duplicates function calls into both "
"branches of an if-statement -- a perfectly sound optimization on CPUs, but "
"it breaks GPU barrier semantics where all threads in a block must converge "
"at the same `bar.sync` instruction. cuda-oxide currently disables "
"JumpThreading for device code (`-Z mir-enable-passes=-JumpThreading`). A "
"proper solution would teach the compiler about convergence requirements so "
"it can optimize around them instead of disabling the pass entirely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:419
msgid "Shared memory access patterns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:421
msgid ""
"The borrow checker cannot reason about whether thread 0 writing `smem[0]` "
"and thread 1 writing `smem[1]` is safe -- it sees `&mut smem` and rejects "
"it. `DisjointSlice` solves the unique-index-write pattern, but not "
"cooperative patterns like reductions, scans, or producer/consumer pipelines "
"where multiple threads intentionally access overlapping regions with "
"synchronization between phases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:428
msgid "Warp-level convergence"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:430
msgid ""
"Operations like `shfl_sync` and `ballot_sync` require that all threads named "
"in the participation mask are actually converged at the call site. The type "
"system cannot enforce this today. If threads have diverged and you pass a "
"full mask, you get a silent hang -- the worst kind of bug, because there is "
"no crash and no error message, just a kernel that never finishes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:436
msgid "Memory space awareness"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:438
msgid ""
"GPU memory has distinct address spaces -- global, shared, local, TMEM. A "
"`&mut` to shared memory is visible to every thread in the block; a `&mut` to "
"local memory is private to one thread. The borrow checker treats them "
"identically. This is conservative (it rejects some safe programs) but never "
"unsound (it does not accept unsafe ones). Still, a memory-space-aware borrow "
"checker could accept more programs without `unsafe`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:445
msgid "Why these are solvable"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:447
msgid ""
"The building blocks already exist in Rust's type system. They need to be "
"extended, not reinvented:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "Idea"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "What It Solves"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Execution-resource-aware types**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"Functions annotated with their execution level (grid / block / warp / "
"thread). A barrier call inside a divergent branch becomes a compile-time "
"error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Memory views**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"Generalized parallel access patterns -- like `DisjointSlice` but covering "
"blocked, striped, transposed, and composed layouts. Type-checked race-"
"freedom at scale."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid "**Extended borrow checking for sync**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:372
msgid ""
"Statically enforce that barriers cannot be forgotten, placed at divergent "
"control flow, or duplicated by the optimizer. Convergence in the type system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:456
msgid ""
"All of this is compile-time analysis. The generated PTX is identical to what "
"you would write by hand -- the safety net disappears at code generation. "
"Zero runtime cost."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:460
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide is well-positioned to deliver this incrementally. The real "
"`rustc` borrow checker already runs on device code. The IR infrastructure "
"(pliron dialects) supports GPU-aware analysis passes. The full compilation "
"pipeline from MIR to PTX is under our control. And each new safety check is "
"additive -- existing kernels keep compiling while new ones get stronger "
"guarantees."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:468
msgid "Writing safe kernels: a cheat sheet"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:470
msgid "The default path"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:472
msgid "For most kernels, start here:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:474
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn my_kernel(input: &[f32], mut output: DisjointSlice<f32>) {\n"
"    if let Some((out, idx)) = output.get_mut_indexed() {\n"
"        *out = transform(input[idx.get()]);\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:483
msgid ""
"For const-stride 2D, parameterise the slice and ask for the const index:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:485
msgid ""
"#[kernel]\n"
"pub fn tile_kernel(mut output: DisjointSlice<f32, Index2D<1024>>) {\n"
"    if let Some((out, _idx)) = output.get_mut_indexed() {\n"
"        *out = ...;\n"
"    }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:494
msgid "The rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:496
msgid "Use `DisjointSlice` for all mutable outputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:497
msgid "Use `&[T]` for all read-only inputs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:498
msgid ""
"For 1D grids, declare `launch_contract(domain = 1, ...)` and use a prepared "
"launch. Inside the kernel, default to `get_mut_indexed()`. If you need the "
"index for arithmetic against multiple slices, fall back to the explicit "
"pair: `let idx = thread::index_1d(); slice.get_mut(idx)`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:502
msgid ""
"For const-stride 2D grids, parameterise the slice as `DisjointSlice<T, "
"Index2D<S>>` and use `get_mut_indexed()` or `thread::index_2d::<S>()`. "
"Mismatched strides are a compile error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:505
msgid ""
"For runtime strides, reach for `unsafe { thread::index_2d_runtime(n) }` with "
"a `Runtime2DIndex`-tagged slice. The `unsafe` is the contract that every "
"thread used the same `n`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:508
msgid ""
"Always bounds-check via `get_mut()` / `get_mut_indexed()` (both return "
"`Option`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:511
msgid ""
"If the kernel body compiles without `unsafe`, it satisfies the device-side "
"part of the proof. Race freedom also requires a matching prepared launch, or "
"an explicit unsafe proof for a raw configuration."
msgstr ""

