#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:525
msgid "The `SAFETY` comment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:527
msgid ""
"For every `unsafe` block, document *why* the invariants hold. Not what the "
"code does -- the code already says that -- but why this particular usage is "
"safe:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:531
msgid ""
"// SAFETY: Only lane 0 of each warp executes this branch.\n"
"// Warp indices (gid / 32) are unique across warps, so no two\n"
"// threads write to the same output element.\n"
"if warp::lane_id() == 0 {\n"
"    let warp_idx = gid.get() / 32;\n"
"    unsafe { *partial_sums.get_unchecked_mut(warp_idx) = warp_sum; }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:541
msgid ""
"This is not ceremony. When a kernel data-races at 2 AM and you are staring "
"at a `compute-sanitizer` log, past-you's safety comments are the fastest "
"path to the bug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../gpu-safety/the-safety-model.md:546
msgid ""
"If you cannot write a convincing `SAFETY` comment for an `unsafe` block, "
"that is a signal that the invariant is not actually maintained. Restructure "
"the code until the argument is obvious, or use a safe API instead."
msgstr ""

